In the present study, to discuss the performance of the TiCN-based cermet as a solar selective absorber, we perform ab initio optical analyses for this cermet, focusing on its major components of W, WC, TiC, and TiN. Systematic investigations of ab initio optical calculations have been performed for TiN and TiC in a face-centered cubic (fcc) structure7,8 and transition metals including W in a body-centered cubic (bcc) structure9, but no such calculations have been performed for WC in a hexagonal closed pack (hcp) structure. We will show that the WC has considerably sharp plasma edge around 0.6 eV (2 μ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\upmu$$\end{document}m), which is a highly desirable aspect for the solar absorber. We will discuss the microscopic origin of this low-energy plasma excitation in terms of an ab initio dielectric analysis.

